Or that the chair of the Federal Reserveâ€™s name is Jerome Powell and heâ€™s not Black? Itâ€™s him not being Black, right? Did his parents lose a bet? If you havenâ€™t heard, Jerome in the House, Without a Doubt and the Feds have been fighting for their mf life trying to control the raging inflation in the United States. Based on my life experiences, there seem to be three stages of grief, with each stage becoming more apparent and noticeable. Itâ€™s Anger, Denial and finally, Nigga. Jerome Jenkins Powell IV and the Federal Reserve are currently at â€˜Nigga.â€™ The Federal Reserve recently raised interest rates by 75 bases points, or .75%. â€˜.75%, thatâ€™s nothing,â€™ I uttered to myself, even though I probably had a F â€“ in Econ 101. Well, itâ€™s not nothing, unfortunately. This is the highest interest rate increase in 28 years. The Fedâ€™s policies, guidance and decisions are the equivalent of Zeus sending bylaws to his Greek subjects; or Malcom X doing that hand gesture thingy, commanding his Nation of Islam brothers to fall back, as the white cop says, â€œThatâ€™s too much power for one man,â€ or whatever he said in the movie. When Jerome Lamont Powell Jr. raised interest rates this high, with more to come, he is essentially telling us the Feds are freaking the fuck out and are willing to do whatever they can to stop inflation, which includes risking a recession. In BET movie standards, we are at the part where the actions taken at the beginning of the movie are coming back to bite us in the ass. The Kern County Hispanic Chamber of Commerce would like to take this opportunity to honor trailblazing women in business and leadership within our community.Â  Itâ€™s an honor to introduce you to Maria Coward, owner of La Costa Mariscos.Â  Maria came to the United States as a single mother hoping to build a future for her family. She never imagined that her struggle would give birth to what is now known as one of â€œBakersfieldâ€™s Bestâ€.Â  Maria opened La Costa Mariscos in downtown Bakersfield with 4 employees and a desire to share the flavors of her hometown of Puerto Vallarta with the community.Â  With over 150 employees and now 2 locations, La Costa will celebrate 30 years of business this coming fall.Â  â€œOur involvement with the KCHCC has provided opportunities to serve the community and to network with leaders in Kern County who share the vision to make Bakersfield an even better place to live.â€

Official Statement on the Buffalo Shooting, Replacement Theory, and White Supremacy: With broken hearts we mourn the senseless loss of 10 beloved children of God who were killed in a grocery store in Buffalo, N.Y., on May 14. Celestine Chaney, Roberta Drury, Katherine Massey, Heyward Patterson, Aaron Salter, Pearl Young, Ruth Whitfield, Margus Morrison, Andre Mackneil, and Geraldine Talley were civil rights activists, community volunteers, parents, siblings, and friends. They were victims of a direct attack on a Black community â€” an attack that is emblematic of a rising wave of violence driven by white supremacists in the U.S. The alleged shooter sought to do more than kill. It was his intent to use this act of terrorism to promote the hateful ideology that drove his actions. In extensive writings shared publicly at the time of the attack, he stated clearly his fear that immigrants and Americans of color are being used to dilute white culture and political power. This â€œreplacement theoryâ€ â€” once a fringe political view â€” has been more widely circulated in recent years as some Republican politicians and pundits have used their platforms to amplify this message, legitimizing its place in conservative political culture. As a result, a growing number of citizens and leaders now sanction elements of this theory. The rhetoric supporting it is increasingly violent, xenophobic, and antisemitic, fracturing the bonds that sustain our pluralistic society. America began with a claim that each individual was created equally and endowed by God with certain inalienable rights. We must embrace this claim with conviction. It is the reason our nation came to be. And because of this founding ideal, this country does not belong â€” and never has belonged â€” only to one race, one ethnicity, one religion, one culture. Those clinging to bigotry and white supremacy commit â€œblasphemy against the American creed.â€ As members of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, we are committed to the doctrine that â€œall are alike unto Godâ€ and that â€œGod is no respecter of persons.â€ An increasingly multiracial society is a welcome fulfillment of our national promise. People of diverse backgrounds living together in peace will be the hallmark of Zion. We echo President M. Russell Ballardâ€™s call â€œto embrace Godâ€™s children compassionately and eliminate any prejudice, including racism, sexism, and nationalism.â€ White supremacy is a corrupting ideology. It is rooted in individual and cultural pride. It is driven by fear and seeks to spread fear that corrupts our nation, churches, schools, and homes. Because we know that â€œperfect love casteth out fear,â€ we cannot be passive in the face of this rising evil. We must each work boldly and actively to root out racism and create a just peace in our own hearts and in our communities. This is not easy or comfortable work; it will require courage, great love, and ongoing concrete action. As we welcome others with charity and seek unity in the midst of our differences, we lay the foundations of Zion. We encourage all to â€œrenounce war and proclaim peace.â€ https://library.mormonwomenforethicalgovernment.org/official-statement-buffalo-shooting-replacement-theory-white-supremacy/ What concrete actions can you take or are you taking to root out racism? Reflection Stillness is not part of ordinary life in our society. We are always doing, going, rushing or talking. Cell phones are our constant connection with life outside of ourselves. We are not used to quiet or time for our own thinking, Yet, stillness is part of the awareness of the presence of the Sacred which we call prayer. It involves no commotion or agitation. Rather, to be still is to seek a serenity, a calm, a tranquility of being. We exchange our usual business, noise and activity for silence and quiet. We are free. We become aware. In experiencing stillness we can touch into our inner selves and open ourselves to the Holy Mystery within and around us. . Prayer I will bless you as long as I live; in your name I will lift up my hands Psalm 63 Action Review the times for stillness in your day. Where can you make this happen realistically? Suggested Readings At the mountain of God, Horeb, Elijah came to a cave where he took shelter. Then the Lord said to him, â€œGo outside and stand on the mountain before the Lord; the Lord will be passing by.â€ A strong and heavy wind was rending the mountains and crushing rocks before the Lordâ€” but the Lord was not in the wind. After the wind there was an earthquakeâ€” but the Lord was not in the earthquake. After the earthquake there was fireâ€” but the Lord was not in the fire. After the fire there was a tiny whispering sound. When he heard this, Elijah hid his face in his cloak and went and stood at the entrance of the cave. 1 Kings 19:9a Be still and know that I am God Psalm 46:10 Only in silence does man succeed in hearingâ€¦the voice of God, which really makes him free. Pope John Paul II In the business of this day Grant me a stillness of seeing, O God. In the conflicting voices of my heart Grant me a calmness of hearing, Letâ€¦my words and my actions Be rooted in a silent certainty of your presence. Let my passions for lifeâ€¦ Be grounded in the experience of your stillness. J.Philip Newell Within you, there is a stillness and a sanctuary to which you can retreat at any time and be yourself. Hermann Hesse Sometimes you need to sit lonely on the floor in a quiet room in order to hear your own voice and not let it drown in the noise of others. Charlotte Eriksson In the midst of movement and chaos, keep stillness inside of you. Deepak Chopra My heart is tuned to the quietness that the stillness of nature inspires. Inayat Khan Learning how to be still, to really be still and let life happen â€“ that stillness becomes a radiance. Morgan Freeman

The Warner Bros. Discovery Access Programs Early Career Bootcamp is an opportunity for underrepresented talent to experience what a career in the entertainment industry entails. If youâ€™re interested in a career in entertainment, this week-long bootcamp is for you! The curriculum will cover the lifespan of a TV show with topics ranging from Network Development to Post-Production, through several roundtable discussions with up-and-coming talent and junior executives. Facilitators will lead practical conversations on breaking-in and offer tangible tools to jump start their careers. Scheduled for August to September. Eligibility Criteria: Early career professionals with strong interest in learning about different facets of the entertainment industry (from creative to corporate), 1-3 years of work experience in the industry (highly preferred), Must be able to work in the US, Must be 19 years of age or older. Apply by June 12 at 5pm CST here: https://illuminatives.org/the-future-is-indigenous/ #Careers #Entertainment #Writers #Indigenous #TVandFilm #NativeAmerican #RepresentationMatters

When Priscilla came to us in 2020, she had been rescued from a life of solitary confinement living in her families basement. Overfed and with hooves that had never been trimmed, Priscilla was unable to walk most of the time. When she had assistance, she would get outside for a few moments, but didnâ€™t enjoy it. The grass and weeds were heavily overgrown, her belly would drag and be scratched, she would trip over her hooves and step on her belly. Once Priscilla was rescued she was given time to grieve the life she had known, got immediate hoof and medical attention, and began a road to recovery with a healthy diet. Today she has zero mobility issues and enjoys living in a herd with her friends. $2 Tuesday Club helped save her life. Last year, Juneteenth was declared a federal holiday. However, for more than 150 years, the African American community has celebrated Juneteenth National Independence Day, also called Emancipation Day or Freedom Day. The holiday commemorates the end of slavery in the United States, observed annually on June 19. This year, the Daughters of Mary Magdalene and the City of Savannah will host the Original Juneteenth Festival Saturday, June 18, from 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. at Wells Park, also known as 38th Street Park. The honorees recognized at the festival are Big Boi from the Emmy award-winning rap group Outkast, the late Mrs. Dorothy Johnson, an award-winning comedian, and Neeali Muhammad, this yearâ€™s Juneteenth scholar. There will be live entertainment, such as the Tommy Stokes Band, E. Larry McDuffie, and the St. John Baptist Male Choir and Brother Balance, to name a few. Make plans to stop by and participate in the cultural festivities. This is one event you donâ€™t want to miss!

BWHI will be hosting a maternal mental health webinar titled "The Path To Perinatal Mental Wellness: A Missing Link to Improving Black Maternal Health Outcomes." The event will take place Thursday, January 27th, from 3:00 pm - 4:15 pm EST. This webinar will demystify perinatal mental health and mood disorders, discuss why Black birthing people are falling through the cracks for screening and care, and the path to wellness. You will have the chance to ask our panel of experts questions and discuss a variety of issues including maternal mental health statistics, gaps in maternal mental health research treatment, mindfulness approaches to stress and anxiety, current policies that advocate for maternal mental health, and much more. You can join this event by using the link provided. To RSVP, please email Alanna Murrell, our Special Projects Manager for a personal calendar invite. We hope to see you there!
